Background and Motivation
Stroke is a health condition that require immediate medical attention at its onset on a person
When the blood supply to a portion of the brain is interrupted, a dangerous medical condition
known as a stroke can result. It is life-threatening and It is the second greatest cause of death
and disability in the world, accounting for almost 11% of all deaths recorded, (Ghazalpour et al.,
2019; Phan et al., 2019; Qureshi et al., 2019; Yan et al., 2019; Mozaffarian et al, 2019 ).
Early identification of individuals at high risk of stroke is crucial for implementing preventive
measures and reducing the incidence of this condition. With the advent of machine learning,
there has been a growing interest in using these algorithms to predict stroke risk based on
patient data.
Some machines learning algorithms that will aid stroke risk prediction include logistic
regression, decision trees, random forest, support vector machines, and artificial neural
networks. In this paper, I will explore the application of various machine learning algorithms for
stroke risk prediction and assess their performance in terms of accuracy and specificity. This
study aims to contribute to the development of effective tools for stroke prediction and early
intervention. I would attempt to find answers to the following research questions:
1. How accurately can machine learning algorithms predict the risk of stroke based on
patient data?
2. Which machine learning algorithms are most effective for predicting stroke risk?
3. Which patient characteristics and clinical factors are most strongly associated with
stroke risk?
It is my believe that this study will add to existing body of knowledge, and guide policy
implementations not only in the health sector but all sectors that value the wellbeing and
health of its workforce.
Aims and Objectives
1. To determine patient characteristics and clinical factors that are most strongly
correlated with stroke risk?
2. To determine how accurately machine learning algorithms can predict the risk of stroke
based on patient data?
3. To determine which machine learning algorithm is most effective for predicting stroke
risk
Research Methodology
This study was undertaken with a secondary data source
(https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/fedesoriano/stroke-prediction-dataset.). Our dataset has
columns and rows.
The Integrated development environment for this study was Google Colab, this because of its
ease of use. Our stroke prediction data set was imported and displayed with the Help of python
pandas libracy. Every other libraries and modules were imported.
After loading the dataset I had to inspect the data set to ascertain duplications missing values
and statistical inference. It was siscovered that body mass index column had a null values, I had
to replace the null values with the average BMI per age group
The dataset was appropriately cleaned to remove null values and subjected to exploratory data
analysis with python. I transformed the categorical variables in my dataset to numeric using
label encoder. I chose label encoder because of its flexibility and ease of use.
I used the sklearn library to split my data into training and testing set, using a test-size of 20%.
The rationale behind this training-testing ratio is to feed my model with enough data to
increase accuracy. The stage was then set to predict stroke risk using
I employed classification algothrithms and classifiers to build my model and test its accuracy.
The algortithms and classifier used are:
1. Logistic Regression
2. Support Vector Machine.
3. Decision Tree
4. Artificial Neural Network
Literature review.
Machine Learning: This is a form of artificial intelligence (AI), machine learning uses algorithms
and statistical models to teach computers how to recognise patterns in data and use that
knowledge to forecast or make decisions. This is achieved by providing the algorithm with a
sizable dataset of examples of input data and the desired output or outcome, and allowing the
algorithm to modify its internal parameters or weights in response to feedback from the
dataset (Alpaydin, 2010; Jordan and Mitchell, 2015). There are three types of machine learning;
The supervised machine learning algorithms uses labelled input and output data, while the
unsupervised type of machine learning does not. The unsupervised algorithms try to discover
hidden pattern in an unlabelled dataset. The reinforcement learning works with the stick and
carrot approach. It rewards desired behaviours and punishes an undesired behaviour.
Logistic Regression: it is a classification algorithm in machine learning, it falls under the
supervised classes of machine learning algorithms.
Support Vector Machine: This is supervised machine learning algorithm that can predict
both regression and classification problems, but it better predicts classification problems. It is
built to find a hyperplane that distinctly classifies the data set. Hyperplanes are decision
boundaries that assist in data classification
Decision Tree Classifier: A decision tree is a supervised machine learning models that
decision represents decisions and likely outcomes in the form of trees, including random
events.
Artificial Neural Networks: This is an artificial intelligence technique, it instructs computers to
analyse data in a manner modelled after the human brain. Deep learning is a sort of machine
learning that employs interconnected neurons or nodes in a layered framework to mimic the
human brain. Computers can make intelligent decisions with minimal human intervention
thanks to neural networks. This is why they can learn and model complex, nonlinear
relationships between input and output data (Amazon Web Services 2022).

From the heat map in fig 6, it is obvious that:

Stroke is positive correlated with ever_married at 0.11 correlation coefficient.
In inference, the elderly should better manage their health; rest more, exercise often
and stick to a heavy diet to avoid coming down with stroke.
Every attempt to reduce blood pressure and blood sugar level reduces the chances of
having stroke.
There is a correlation between marital status and stroke. Everyone married and
unmarried should maintain a healthy living to avoid stroke.
Setting up Machine Learning Algorithms
The first thing we did was to choose our output and input variables and put them in a numpy
array
We had to standardize our input variables with Zscore, and then split our variables into training
and testing in the ratio of 80:20.
Logistic Regression Algorithm: We did a logistic regression on the training and testing
data set and got a high accuracy of 0.949119373776908
Support Vector Machine: Another algorithm was employed to test and train our model;
the support vector machine gave us an accuracy of 0.949119373776908
Decision Tree Classifier: This classifier gave us the least accuracy, at 0.9481409001956947
Artificial Neaural Network: This algorithm is the most accurate of all our algorithms at
0.9500978473581213. We used an epoch of 200 and a size of 20 for our training
The study concludes that artificial neural network is the the best algorithm to predict stroke risk
Limitation
The output column of my dataset was skewed towards those without stroke and attempt to
normalize it was not successful.

I also learnt that average glucose level is another factor that can make one predisposed to a
